title: Farm Hand one versus two
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

The main difference between Farm and Livestock Hand Level 1 (FLH1) and Level 2 (FLH2) under the Pastoral Award 2020 comes down to **experience and the level of supervision required**. FLH1 is the true entry-level, "learning the ropes" stage, while FLH2 is for employees who have gained some basic experience and can work with more independence .

Here is a detailed comparison of the classifications as they apply from **1 April 2025**.

### 📊 FLH1 vs. FLH2: A Detailed Comparison

| Feature | Farm and Livestock Hand Level 1 (FLH1) | Farm and Livestock Hand Level 2 (FLH2) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Primary Criteria** | Less than 6 months of experience in the industry . | 6 to 12 months of experience in the industry . |
| **Supervision Level** | Works under **direct supervision** either individually or in a team environment . | Works under **routine supervision** either individually or in a team environment . |
| **Typical Duties** | • Routine mustering<br>• Routine fence repairs<br>• Aerial stock sighting<br>• Repetitive packing/unpacking<br>• Kitchen/cooking assistance (no food prep)<br>• Operate milking plant (dairy)  | • Sort and cut out stock<br>• Sort and brand yarded stock<br>• Basic non-trades maintenance<br>• Fence repairs<br>• Boundary riding<br>• Forklift, tractor, or winch operation<br>• Assist a tradesperson  |
| **Adult Hourly Rate** (FT/PT, effective July 2025) | **$24.28** per hour  | **$24.95** per hour  |
| **Adult Weekly Rate** (FT, effective July 2025) | **$922.70**  | **$948.00**  |
| **Casual Hourly Rate** (includes 25% loading) | **$30.35** per hour  | **$31.19** per hour  |

### 📝 Important Notes on Progression and Variations

There are a few critical points to understand about how these levels work in practice:

- **Automatic vs. Competency-Based Progression**: The primary method for moving from Level 1 to Level 2 is completing 6 months of employment. However, the award allows for an employee to progress to the next level **before the six months are up** if they can demonstrate the required competency or achieve a relevant qualification .
- **Different Roles, Same Level**: It's important to know that the FLH1 and FLH2 classifications cover a wide range of job titles beyond just "farm hand". For example, a "Station Cook" or "Cattle Farm Worker" with less than 6 months of experience is classified as Level 1, while those with more than 6 months move to Level 2 .
- **Unchanged Higher Levels**: While the definitions for Levels 1 and 2 changed on 1 April 2025, the progression requirements for higher levels remain the same. Progression to **FLH3** typically requires **12 months** of experience, and to **FLH5** about **2 years** .

To summarize, the transition from FLH1 to FLH2 represents an employee's first major step up from a novice to a developing farm hand, reflected in both their duties and their pay rate.

